{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620654"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:45:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:45:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16640"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16640"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.32,0,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76222"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9331"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61726"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"5061"},{"type":"tags","id":"5191"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22376"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76222"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old child with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) has been prescribed methylphenidate. The parent reports reduced appetite and difficulty finishing meals since starting treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of appetite suppression?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits dopamine and noradrenaline reuptake","Decreases gastrointestinal peristalsis","Modifies central taste processing","Induces gastric inflammation","Accelerates metabolic processes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe appetite suppression is caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting dopamine and noradrenaline reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E. This increases synaptic concentrations of these neurotransmitters in appetite control centres of the brain, leading to reduced hunger and food intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases gastrointestinal peristalsis\u003C/strong\u003E - methylphenidate\u0027s effects on appetite are primarily mediated through central nervous system mechanisms rather than direct effects on the gastrointestinal system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModifies central taste processing\u003C/strong\u003E - there is no evidence that methylphenidate directly affects taste pathways\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduces gastric inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - while some gastrointestinal side effects may occur, the appetite suppression is centrally mediated through neurotransmitter effects\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccelerates metabolic processes\u003C/strong\u003E - although stimulants can have minor effects on metabolism, this is not the primary mechanism for reduced appetite\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDecreased appetite is one of the most common adverse effects of methylphenidate, along with insomnia, anxiety, and mild increases in heart rate and blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Methylphenidate blocks dopamine and noradrenaline reuptake transporters, increasing synaptic concentrations of these neurotransmitters.","Common adverse effects of methylphenidate include decreased appetite, insomnia, and anxiety.","Stimulant medications require careful monitoring due to their cardiovascular and psychiatric side effects."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61726"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16640"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61726"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:29:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:30:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9331"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76222"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"at